Project: Investigation of Soccer Players' Performance¶

  • Introduction

  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

I've selected the European Soccer Database to investigate, due to my passion on understanding performance. This database includes information related to soccer for seasons 2008 to 2016. I've opened the file using DB Browser, since it's a ".sqlite" file. Within DB Browser I was able to better check the contents of the database (in "Browse Data"), which includes 8 tables, with the following information:

  • Country (mentions included countries)
  • League (mentions included leagues and their respective countries)
  • Match (info about soccer matches, of where and when they occurred, which teams and players played, players' positions in the field, scores, stats related to team performance during the game, the odds of winning, drawing or losing by 10 different providers)
  • Player (mentions included players, their birthday, height and weight)
  • Player_Attributes (info about each player in terms of their attributes, such as overall rating, potential, preferred foot, rate of attacking and defensive work, scores related to how good they are in various skills and general attributes, and when these measures were updated)
  • Team (mentions included teams)
  • Team_Attributes (info about each team like their scores in various attributes and its respective class, and when these measures were updated)
  • sqlite_sequence (unrelated to soccer information and unnecessary for this investigation)

Questions for Analysis¶

Taking into account all information we have and my own curiosity, I've come up with 3 questions:

  1. How do team results tend to differ by team overall age?

This is a type of question very common in recruitment processes, because there is a lot of preconceived ideas about age in certain tasks' performance. I am curious to know if, for example, there are age differences in winning and losing teams.

  1. How do team results tend to differ by team overall weight?

Is it possible that teams have different results depending on their weight?

  1. How do team results tend to differ by team overall height?

Does height seem to be an advantage, disadvantage or irrelevant? (although this is not a study about causation, but I'm pointing out the origin of my motivation to these questions, so it would be a starting point)

Data Wrangling¶

In order to answer my questions, I'll only need the tables Match and Player. For that reason, I've exported these 2 tables, with only the columns I believe to be necessary in the Player table (I'll clean the Match table as necessary), and I'll merge them whenever necessary using python. I've used the following SQL code to do it:

SELECT * FROM Match

SELECT player_api_id, birthday, height, weight FROM Player

I downloaded the respective CSV files.

Data Cleaning¶

First, let's create the dataframe we need for the first question. We need it to have something like the following columns:

  • match_api_id
  • team_api_id
  • Overall_Age
  • Overall_Height
  • Overall_Weight
  • Win_Rate
  • Draw_Rate
  • Loss_Rate

Although we'll also include the goals scored and suffered to see if there are also differences in terms of that performance.

    df_questions.drop("player_api_id", axis=1, inplace=True)

In [21]:
# Before we concatenate, let's get the match result per team, so we'll have all wanted information after
df_home_temp["goal_dif"] = df_home_temp["goals_scored"] - df_home_temp["goals_suff"]
df_away_temp["goal_dif"] = df_away_temp["goals_scored"] - df_away_temp["goals_suff"]

df_home_temp.loc[df_home_temp["goal_dif"] < 0, "result"] = "L"
df_home_temp.loc[df_home_temp["goal_dif"] > 0, "result"] = "W"
df_home_temp.loc[df_home_temp["goal_dif"] == 0, "result"] = "D"

df_away_temp.loc[df_away_temp["goal_dif"] < 0, "result"] = "L"
df_away_temp.loc[df_away_temp["goal_dif"] > 0, "result"] = "W"
df_away_temp.loc[df_away_temp["goal_dif"] == 0, "result"] = "D"

# We'll have to repeat this task a couple of times, so let's create a function for it
#I'm going to need this list
match_result_labels = ["D","L","W"]

#I'll need a function to create a data frame with filtered results from df_question
def df_generator(column_for_ratio, ratio_labels):
    '''
    Returns new dataframes for every label we want
        
        Parameters:
            column_for_ratio(str): column we want to filter, must be within quotation marks
            ratio_labels(list): labels we want to get a dataframe from, must be present in column_for_ratio
            
        Returns:
            df_[label]: a new dataframe for each label within ratio_labels,a dn print their names
    
    '''
    for label in ratio_labels:
        globals()['df_%s' %label] = df_questions[df_questions[column_for_ratio] == str(label)]
        print("Generated: df_"+str(label))
In [54]:
# Now I'll need a function that will find the ratios we want

def find_ratio(column_categories, ratio_labels):
    '''
    Returns ratios for labels in every category defined
    
        Parameters:
            column_categories(str): Name of the column with categories we want to see the ratios in. Must be in quotation marks
            ratio_labels(list): labels that we want to know the ratio, per category in column_categories
        
        Returns:
            [label]_ratio_[column_category]: A new variable which contains the ratio of the label within a category and print it
    '''
    for label in ratio_labels:
        globals()['%s_ratio_%s' %(label, column_categories)] = globals()['df_%s' %label].groupby(column_categories)\
        .team_api_id.count() / df_questions.groupby(column_categories).team_api_id.count()
        print("Found the ratio: "+str(label)+"_ratio_"+str(column_categories))

Unfortunately, because the created height groups have very different frequencies (wasn't able to get them closer to each other due to less diversified values) this last graph shows that the tallest and very short teams are always in a higher ratio (because, in fact, there are more teams in those categories than the rest), so we can't take many conclusions from this graph.

However, since the short and very tall groups have frequencies more close to each other we can compare them, and we can see that in the losing teams we can find more short teams than the tallest ones, but only with a small difference.

In winning teams we can find more of the tallest teams than of the short teams.

Conclusions¶

Research Question 1: How do team results tend to differ by team overall age?

I've found out that in the present data:

  • The average number of goals scored and suffered were lower in older teams and higher in younger ones.In other words, older teams scored and suffered less goals than younger ones;
  • The ratio of wins is lower in older teams, while the ratio of losses is higher.
  • Also, we can find more often younger teams in the winning group than older teams, and the oldest teams are also more common in the losing group.

Summary: So, although older teams have suffered less goals, everything else was worst for them, less goals scored, lost more than they have won and even when we compare between the age categories they lose more frequently and win less. It seems like younger teams were the clear winners in terms of match results statistics.

Research Question 2: How do team results tend to differ by team overall weight?

I've found out that in the present data:

  • Heavier teams, on average, scored more goals and suffered less;
  • Lighter teams lost more matches than what they have won, and heavier teams have won more matches than lost;
  • There are more lighter teams in the losing group and the heavier teams are more common in the winning group.

Summary: So heavier teams seem to have scored more goals, suffered less, won more games than the ones they lost and are weight category most present in winning teams. The lightest group, however, is the opposite, so it looks like heavier teams were the clear winners in terms of match results

Research Question 3: How do team results tend to differ by team overall height?

I've found out that in the present data:

  • On average, taller teams scored more goals, but they are hardly any differences between height groups in terms of suffered goals;
  • However, taller teams scored more than what they have suffered, and shorter teams suffered more than what they have scored;
  • Slightly heavier teams had more matches where they scored a lot of goals
  • There are no differences in winning and losing rates in any of the height groups, they all seem to lose and win around the same number of games;
  • In losing teams, there are more short teams than the tallest ones, and the tallest ones are more frequent in the winning group, compared to the short.

Summary: Tallest teams seem to have scored more and, compared to the short teams, were the ones more often to win the game and less often to lose, so it looks like they were the better teams, but there are small differences in most of the data.

Additional Research

  • It would be important to know if these differences we have found are actually statisticaly significant, because they might not be strong enough;

  • Professional soccer teams don't have many differences between ages, weight and height, so it would be interesting to have data on non professional matches, which should have a higher variety of those values between players.

  • I would also like to do a lot more reasearch on the other tables, like with the Player_Attributes table, but a lot of information is stored in xml so it would require more time for me to do it, since I am not at ease with that type of language, yet.

Limitations¶

Because the distribution of height values is not much broad, it was hard to define height groups with around the same number of teams. That made it hard to compare between groups since their ratios were off, not because of actual performance results, but simply because there were more teams in certain groups than others.

It's also important to note that while we can easily update age between match seasons, since we have the birthday date of each player and not an age number in our source of information, we can't do the same with height and weight values. I don't have any information about when these values were assessed, and there are no updates between seasons, so my conclusions regarding height and weight data are not realistic because players could have different values for each match and we are not aware of that.
